segments.text: Unless you can prove that, the programs will have a salutary economic impact on the state.
It's needed desperately for some reason.
I'm not sure that we can prove that right now.
Do you think that with the new dean coming in, that it might be possible to have a new degree program at any college because of the new dean?
He will certainly have a honeymoon period during which time the provost office and others will try to meet his interest and his demands.
I don't know that that will be a real high priority for him.
We've not talked about that at all.
As far as new programs for the college are concerned, the program of visual studies is probably more important for the campus as well.
I would expect that would occupy more of his attention than the program in Irvington at this point.
The accreditation team was surprised that there was no undergraduate lead in degree program for the MEP.
And this would be an appropriate vehicle for that.
And of course, we've had continual frustration within the college in reaching undergraduate students with our undergraduate planning courses.
Yeah.
Historically, the pre-architecture students have not taken planning courses, which is crazy.
Not even the architecture students take part in classes.
That's true.
Which is odd.
It seems to me that a course in planning should be required for architecture students, and certainly for undergraduates toward the end of their undergraduate academic career.
Yeah, I think later rather than earlier.
They don't have vocabulary to understand what we're talking about until they're juniors or seniors.
Some of them don't even know where they are when they're freshmen or sophomores, let alone what they're doing here and what they're studying.
Or what the strange discipline might be that they've never heard of before.
Don, can you think of anything else you'd like to add?
OK, well, I want to thank you for your time.
And you'll be receiving in due course a transcript, which you may mark up in whatever way you want and then return it to me.
And that'll be used to write the history of accounting education in Texas.
Thank you.
Thank you.
